sed. if `on_probe_fail: skip` means the unit gets skipped entirely when the probe fails, then the apply block never runs, which defeats the purpose of initialization. I need to reconsider what this directive actually does in the KARMA framework. Looking at the precondition log, the `mongo_env_ready` probe actually ran successfully, but then the apply block never showed up in the output—which suggests it was skipped even though the probe passed. That's backwards from what I'd expect; if the probe succeeds, the apply should run, not skip.\n\nWait, I think I'm reading this wrong. The probe passing means the StatefulSet already exists, so the apply gets skipped to avoid a destructive reset. But that means the fault injection (breaking member 1) never happened either, so the cluster stayed healthy instead of entering the degraded state the initialize case is supposed to handle.\n\nNow the `mongo_seed_fixture` probe failed because there weren't enough documents, so its apply ran and seeded the data. The oracle checks should all pass now—hosts are correct, the replica set has 1 primary and 2 secondaries, the StatefulSet is at 3/3, and we have the seeded documents. So the system is already stable.\n\nMy role as the agent is to verify the replica set is healthy and stable, which it already appears to be. But I should double-check the precondition logs to make sure I'm not missing something that actually needs fixing. I need to verify the current state of the replica set and determine if any fixes are needed, then write the submit.txt file if everything checks out.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2529,"cache_read_input_tokens":54231,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2529},"output_tokens":23,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"3